<!--Toyohiwake no Mikoto--><!--Toyohiwake no Mikoto--><!--Toyohiwake no Mikoto--><!--Toyohiwake no Mikoto--><!--Toyohiwake no Mikoto--><!--Toyohiwake no Mikoto--><!--Toyohiwake no Mikoto--> [[Category:豊国の人物]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[zh:豐日別]] <!--zhwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[zh:豐日別]]

{{Infobox Shinto deity | name = Toyohiwake | image = | caption = | generation = | predecessor = | successor = | classification = [[Kunitama]] (Spirit of the Land) | full_name = | alternate_name = {{ill|豊国|ja|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/豊国|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}|other_names = | Rank = | role = Spirit of the land ([[Kunitama]]) | burial_site= | father = [[Izanagi]] | mother = [[:en:Izanami|Izanami]] | siblings = | spouse = | children = | shrines = [[Toyohiwake-no-miya]] and others | blessings = | myths = | related_clans =|qq=draft|qq=draft}} '''Toyohiwake''' ({{lang|ja|豊日別}}) is a deity featured in the [[Kojiki]] and is associated with the creation of Japan's lands.
== Overview == In the section of the [[Kojiki]] describing the [[Kuniumi|creation of the land]], the deities [[Izanagi]] and [[:en:Izanami|Izanami]] gave birth to the great islands of Japan, known as the [[:en:Ōyashima|Ōyashima]]. The island of [[Kyushu]], like [[Iyo-no-futana-shima]] (modern [[Shikoku]]), is said to have one body but four faces, each with its own name. The second face, corresponding to the land of [[Toyokuni]] (modern [[:en:Bungo Province|Bungo Province]]), is called Toyohiwake. The other faces are associated with the lands of [[Chikushi Province|Chikushi]] ([[Shirahiwake]]), [[Hikuni]] ([[Tatehihayahi-toyo-kushibi-nidoriwake]]), and [[Kumaso Province|Kumaso]] ([[Tatehiwake]]).
{{quote|次生筑紫嶋、此嶋亦、身一而有面四、毎面有名、故、筑紫國謂白日別、'''豐國謂豐日別'''、肥國謂建日向日豐久士比泥別自久至泥、以音、熊曾國謂建日別。曾字以音。|古事記}}
Edo-period scholar {{ill|Deguchi Nobuyoshi|ja|出口延佳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Deguchi Nobuyoshi|qq=}} speculated that these names, including Toyohiwake, were the original names of the regions during the [[Age of the Gods]] and that names like Chikushi or Toyokuni were adopted later under the [[Ritsuryō system]].<ref>{{cite book|和書|author=佐藤蔵太郎|year=1905|title=豊後史蹟考|publisher=甲斐書店|location=大分県}}</ref>
== Shrines == Toyohiwake is worshipped at several shrines across Japan, particularly in Kyushu.
=== Toyohiwake-no-miya === The {{ill|Toyohiwake-no-miya|ja|豊日別宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyohiwake-no-miya|qq=}} (豊日別宮) in [[Yukuhashi]], [[:en:Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka Prefecture]], holds a tradition that dates back to Emperor [[:en:Kinmei|Kinmei]]'s reign in the 6th century. According to its lore, the deity Toyohiwake was associated with the god [[Sarutahiko Ōkami|Sarutahiko]], who guided [[Amaterasu]]'s descendant during the celestial descent. Toyohiwake is sometimes equated with Sarutahiko but is understood to have distinct qualities.<ref>{{cite book|和書|editor=佐藤蔵太郎|title=豊後史蹟考|year=1905|publisher=甲斐書店}}</ref>
=== Unzen Shrine === Known locally as {{nihongo|Shimen-gū|四面宮}}, the [[Unzen Shrine]] in Nagasaki Prefecture venerates Toyohiwake and similar four-faced deities. This shrine system spread across the Shimabara Peninsula and is a local center of worship.<ref>[https://shimengu-jinja.jp/ 四面宮会ホームページ]</ref>
=== Takasumi Shrine === Located at the base of Mount [[Hikosan]] in [[Oita Prefecture]], Takasumi Shrine venerates Toyohiwake as a guardian of the region. Known also as the [[Hikosan]] deity, it holds connections to mountain worship traditions.
=== Others === Toyohiwake is also honored at shrines like [[Itouzu Hachiman Shrine]] and [[Yami-no-hama Shrine]]. These shrines emphasize its role as a protector of the land and its people.
== Related Concepts == Toyohiwake is often associated with other [[Kunitama]] (land spirits) and has connections to [[Sarutahiko Ōkami|Sarutahiko]], [[Takamimusubi|Takami-Musubi]], and the mountain deities of northern Kyushu. == See Also == * [[Kuniumi]] * [[List of Japanese deities]] * [[Toyo Province]] * [[Zenpokoenfun]]
